The [[Big East Conference (1979–2013)|Big East Conference]] gave five football awards at the conclusion of every season. The awards were first given in 1991 following the conference's first football season, and last given in 2012 before the conference was restructured as the [[American Athletic Conference]]. The five awards included Offensive Player of the Year, Defensive Player of the Year, Special Teams Player of the Year, Rookie of the Year, and Coach of the Year. Recipients were selected by the votes of the conference's eight head coaches.<ref name=list>{{cite news|url=http://www.bigeast.org/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=92485&SPID=11215&DB_OEM_ID=19400&ATCLID=3631151 |title=Big East Announces 2008 Postseason Football Honors |date=December 10, 2008 |author=Big East Conference |access-date=March 13, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204202404/http://www.bigeast.org/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=92485&SPID=11215&DB_OEM_ID=19400&ATCLID=3631151 |archive-date=4 February 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="2012 list">{{cite web |url=http://www.bigeast.org/portals/5/fls/19400/pdfs/football/2012/2012_Football_Guide_Web.pdf |title=Big East Awards |work=2012 Big East Football Media Guide |publisher=Big East Conference |page=129 |format=PDF |access-date=January 26, 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name="2012 press release">{{cite press release |url=http://www.bigeast.org/tabid/435/article/239991/BIG-EAST-Announces-2012-Postseason-Football-Honors.aspx |title=BIG EAST Announces 2012 Postseason Football Honors |publisher=Big East Conference |date=December 6, 2012 |access-date=January 26, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130320143624/http://www.bigeast.org/tabid/435/article/239991/BIG-EAST-Announces-2012-Postseason-Football-Honors.aspx |archive-date=March 20, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Award recipients included [[Heisman Trophy]] winners, [[National Football League|NFL]] first-round draft picks, and NFL [[NFL Pro Bowl|All-Star]] selections. The [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami Hurricanes]] were the most successful team through the school's tenure with the conference from 1991 to 2004, winning six awards for offensive players, seven for defense, four for special teams, three for Rookie of the Year, and six for Coach of the Year. Every conference member received at least two awards.

[[Donovan McNabb]] of [[Syracuse Orange football|Syracuse]] is the only player to win more than two awards; he was named Rookie of the Year in 1995 and Offensive Player of the Year in 1996, 1997, and 1998. [[Frank Beamer]] of [[Virginia Tech Hokies|Virginia Tech]], [[Dennis Erickson]] of Miami, and [[Brian Kelly (American football coach)|Brian Kelly]] of [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]] were each Coach of the Year three times.

==Offensive Player of the Year==
[[File:Donovan McNabb.jpg|thumb|upright|Donovan McNabb is the only player to be awarded three times.]]
[[File:Santana Moss 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Santana Moss (pictured) and Antonio Bryant in 2000 were the first wide receivers to win.]]
The Offensive Player of the Year was awarded to the player voted most-outstanding at an offensive position. The first two awards were given to [[quarterback]] [[Gino Torretta]] of the [[Miami Hurricanes football|University of Miami]]. In 1992, Torretta was a unanimous selection, the first of only two players to receive that distinction as of 2012. The other unanimous selection was [[running back]] [[Jordan Todman]] of [[UConn Huskies football|Connecticut]] in 2010. There have been three ties: in 1996, 2001, and 2002, and a three-way tie in 2001. Besides Torretta, quarterbacks [[Ken Dorsey]] of Miami and [[Pat White (American football)|Pat White]] of [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] have both been awarded twice; Dorsey's awards in 2001 and 2002 were both ties. [[Donovan McNabb]] was selected three times and became the second overall pick in the [[1999 NFL draft]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.suathletics.com/sports/2005/5/31/dmcnabb.aspx |title=Donovan McNabb, Football, 1995-98 |publisher=Syracuse University |access-date=March 18, 2009}}</ref> Miami has received the most awards, six before leaving the conference in 2004. Only [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]] (who joined in 2005) and [[Temple Owls football|Temple]] (which joined in 1991, was expelled after the 2004 season, and returned in 2012) have no offensive winners.

Of the 27 winners, there were 15 quarterbacks, eight running backs, three [[wide receivers]], and one [[tight end]]. Nine seniors, seven juniors, nine sophomores, and two freshmen were honored.<ref name="2012 list"/><ref name="2012 press release"/>

