==Special Teams Player of the Year==
The Special Teams Player of the Year award was given to the player voted best on [[American football positions#Special teams|special teams]]. The recipient was either be a placekicker, punter, returner, or a position known as a [[gunner (American football)|gunner]]. The first winner was [[Kevin Williams (wide receiver, born 1971)|Kevin Williams]], a returner from Miami. [[Andy Lee (American football)|Andy Lee]], a Pittsburgh punter, and Cincinnati kick returner [[Mardy Gilyard]] were the only players to receive the award more than once.<ref name=pitt>{{cite web |url=http://pittsburghpanthers.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120903aaa.html |title=Fitzgerald and Lee Earn Big East Player of the Year Honors |publisher=University of Pittsburgh |date=December 9, 2003 |access-date=March 20, 2009}}</ref>

There were 24 recipients, with ties in 2002 and 2003. Of the award recipients, 12 were seniors, nine juniors, and three sophomores. Three placekickers won the award, most recently Virginia Tech's [[Shayne Graham]] in 1999. [[Todd Sauerbrun]] was the first punter to win after he was a unanimous selection in 1994.

Notably, Temple players received both the Special Teams Player of the Year and Rookie of the Year (see below) awards in 2012, the first year of the Owls' last Big East tenure.<ref name="2012 press release"/> During Temple's previous tenure in Big East football from 1991 to 2004, the Owls received only one conference award.<ref name="2012 list"/>

